# GridDungeon — Framework vs Data

## Assemblies (see `GridDungeon.Framework.asmdef` / `GridDungeon.Data.asmdef`)

- **`GridDungeon.Framework`** — `Assets/GridDungeon/Framework/**`. Reusable engine/domain code. **Do not reference `GridDungeon.Data`.**
- **`GridDungeon.Data`** — `Assets/GridDungeon/Data/**`. This title only (e.g. exploration UI state, game-specific glue). **May reference Framework.**

## Put new C# here

| In Framework | In Data |
|--------------|---------|
| ScriptableObject **type** definitions (`CreateAssetMenu`), `ActionData`, `CharacterData`, `EncounterData`, `StatusData`, encounter/party/action execution models (`EncounterParty`, `QueuedActions`, `IActionHandler`, …) | Types tightly coupled to **this** game’s UI graphs: `ExplorationUIState`, `MessagesUIState`, `*UIState` under `Data/UI/State`, etc. |
| `ICharacterTemplate` implementors, `CharacterInstance` / `PlayerCharacterInstance` / `EncounterCharacterInstance`, status stack (`IStatus`, factories) | Bridges only if Framework must stay unaware (e.g. `ExplorationPartyBridge` in Framework + wire-up in Data) |

When a type **cannot** live in Framework because it needs `ExplorationUIState` (Data): use a small **bridge** in Framework (callbacks/static accessors) and wire from Data — avoid Framework → Data references.

## Namespace

Keep **`GridDungeon.Core`** unless you introduce a new namespace deliberately (Unity assets/UXML often assume this).

## UI Toolkit / UXML

`data-source-type` must list the **assembly where the type is compiled**:

- Example: `GridDungeon.Core.EncounterRow, GridDungeon.Framework, Version=0.0.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=null`
- UI state types still in Data: use `..., GridDungeon.Data, ...`

Wrong assembly → runtime `TypeLoadException` in `VisualTreeAsset.CloneTree()`.

## Content assets (.asset, prefabs, scenes)

Authoring files may live under `Data/` folders for organization; **script** location defines the **assembly**. After moving scripts, update UXML/prefab/scene **type assembly strings** if they embed full type names.

## Editor

`GridDungeon.Editor` references both assemblies; editor-only drawers can use either side.
